<heading id="E60C818AFFE0FFEA84FDF8A5FA9BF8C2" bold="true" box="[951,1316,1812,1836]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="4" pageId="12" pageNumber="27" reason="0">
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE0FFEA84FDF8A5FA9BF8C2" bold="true" box="[951,1316,1812,1836]" pageId="12" pageNumber="27">
Genus 
<taxonomicName id="7AFB4D65FFE0FFEA834DF8A4FA9BF8C2" authority="Germar, 1817" authorityName="Germar" authorityYear="1817" box="[1031,1316,1812,1836]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Polydrusus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE0FFEA834DF8A4FB3DF8C2" bold="true" box="[1031,1154,1812,1836]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="27">Polydrusus</emphasis>
Germar, 1817
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F5E1656DFFE0FFEB8475F8F6FF67F983" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="12" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="BD4436E6FFE0FFEA8475F8F6FA22F7F3" blockId="12.[831,1437,1861,2078]" pageId="12" pageNumber="27">
We included five samples of this genus belonging to 3 species out of 2 subgenera (
<taxonomicName id="7AFB4D65FFE0FFEA83D8F8D6FCCBF872" authority="Chevrolat, 1869" authorityName="Chevrolat" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Piezocnemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE0FFEA83D8F8D6FAA2F893" box="[1170,1309,1894,1917]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="27">Piezocnemus</emphasis>
Chevrolat, 1869
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7AFB4D65FFE0FFEA84FBF835FA2FF870" authority="K. Daniel &amp; J. Daniel, 1898" authorityName="K. Daniel &amp; J. Daniel" authorityYear="1898" box="[945,1424,1925,1950]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Chlorodrosus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE0FFEA84FBF835FBFDF872" box="[945,1090,1925,1948]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="27">Chlorodrosus</emphasis>
K. Daniel &amp; J. Daniel, 1898
</taxonomicName>
). The species were not retrieved in a monophyletic clade (
<figureCitation id="25C02A63FFE0FFEA840DF875FC37F830" box="[839,904,1989,2014]" captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,186,1908,1929]" captionTargetBox="[155,1408,263,1896]" captionTargetId="graphics@3.[544,992,642,2095]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Best Maximum Likelihood tree as selected by MEGA) based on COI sequences of 142 samples of Curculionoidea (Chrysomelidae obtained by using MEGA 6. Values (over 50 %) of bootstrap support from 100 nodes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1040870/files/figure.svg" pageId="12" pageNumber="27">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, Supp. 1), suggesting that the species concept of 
<taxonomicName id="7AFB4D65FFE0FFEA8475F855FC08F812" authorityName="Germar" authorityYear="1817" box="[831,951,2021,2044]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Polydrusus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE0FFEA8475F855FC08F812" box="[831,951,2021,2044]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="27">Polydrusus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also polyphyletic, which is not really a surprise, regarding the span of morphological variability.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD4436E6FFE1FFEB87DDFEB3FECCFCF2" blockId="13.[151,756,258,796]" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">
In the case of the sibling alpine species 
<taxonomicName id="7AFB4D65FFE1FFEB8536FEB2FE01FED7" authority="Stierlin, 1859" authorityName="Stierlin" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Polydrusus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxus">
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB8536FEB2FEB7FED7" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Polydrusus paradoxus</emphasis>
Stierlin, 1859
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB869EFE93FD38FED7" box="[468,647,290,314]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">/ chaerodrysius</emphasis>
Gredler, 1866 the differences in the COI support the very subtle morphological characters; both species can be distinguished mainly by the form of the scales on their femora (
<bibRefCitation id="D96A4B17FFE1FFEB87BAFE13FE23FE55" author="Germann C." box="[240,412,419,443]" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" pagination="221 - 225" part="85" refString="Germann C. 2012. Beitrag zur Verbreitung der Piezocnemus - Arten in der Schweiz mit der Erstmeldung von Polydrusus (Piezocnemus) chaerodrysius Gredler, 1866 (Coleoptera, Curculionidae). Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 85: 221 - 225." title="Beitrag zur Verbreitung der Piezocnemus - Arten in der Schweiz mit der Erstmeldung von Polydrusus (Piezocnemus) chaerodrysius Gredler, 1866 (Coleoptera, Curculionidae)" type="journal article" year="2012">Germann, 2012</bibRefCitation>
). Thus it can be stated that small morphological differences are mirrored by a considerable genetic distance (K2 distance: 0.048). Furthermore, although from apparently very isolated populations, the samples of 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB860CFD94FE44FDD4" box="[326,507,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">P. chaerodrysius</emphasis>
collected in Valchava GR (sample 103) and Schwarenbach BE (208 km from each other; sample 143 / sample 063) differ in solely 0.2 % (
<tableCitation id="F079035DFFE1FFEB87A4FD33FEF8FD74" box="[238,327,643,666]" captionStart="Tables 1 - 8" captionStartId="11.[151,213,258,279]" captionText="Tables 1 - 8: COI Kimura 2 - Parameter genetic distances for a set of selected samples used in the present study. See the main text for further details." pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Table 6</tableCitation>
). More localities were not discovered at present, despite of several specific excursions inbetween.An explanation could be their parthenogenetical reproduction, where no gene-exchange as in sexual reproduction occurs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD4436E6FFE1FFEB87A9FCD4FD17FC95" blockId="13.[227,680,867,891]" box="[227,680,867,891]" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">
<heading id="E60C818AFFE1FFEB87A9FCD4FD17FC95" bold="true" box="[227,680,867,891]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="4" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" reason="0">
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB87A9FCD4FD17FC95" bold="true" box="[227,680,867,891]" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">
species-pair 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB863AFCD3FD17FC95" bold="true" box="[368,680,867,891]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Phyllobius pyri / vespertinus</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD4436E6FFE1FFEB87DDFC23FF67F983" blockId="13.[151,756,915,1645]" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">
The species status of 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB86CEFC23FDC7FC45" box="[388,632,915,939]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Phyllobius vespertinus</emphasis>
(Fabricius, 1792) was (and still is) highly debated (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="D96A4B17FFE1FFEB8538FC03FF70FC02" author="Dieckmann L." journalOrPublisher="Entomologische Nachrichten" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" pagination="3 - 13" part="1" refString="Dieckmann L. 1979. Phyllobius vespertinus (Fabricius), eine von Ph. pyri (Linne) abzutrennende Art (Col., Curculionidae). Entomologische Nachrichten 1: 3 - 13." title="Phyllobius vespertinus (Fabricius), eine von Ph. pyri (Linne) abzutrennende Art (Col., Curculionidae)" type="journal article" year="1979">Dieckmann, 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="D96A4B17FFE1FFEB87A9FC64FE1FFC02" author="Germann C." box="[227,416,980,1004]" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" pagination="155 - 169" part="84" refString="Germann C. 2011 a. Supplement zur Checkliste der Russelkafer der Schweiz (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea). Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 84: 155 - 169." title="Supplement zur Checkliste der Russelkafer der Schweiz (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea)" type="journal article" year="2011" yearSuffix="a">Germann, 2011a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="D96A4B17FFE1FFEB86F8FC63FD08FC02" author="Alonso-Zarazaga M. A." bookContentInfo="700 pp." box="[434,695,979,1004]" editor="Lobl I" journalOrPublisher="Brill, Leiden" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" refString="Alonso-Zarazaga M. A. 2013. New acts and comments [p. 81]. In: Lobl I., Smetana A. (eds). Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. Vol. 8: Curculionoidea II. Brill, Leiden, 700 pp." title="New acts and comments [p. 81]" type="book" volumeTitle="Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. Vol. 8: Curculionoidea II" year="2013">Alonso-Zarazaga, 2013</bibRefCitation>
) and recently regarded as synonym to 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB8541FC45FDECFBE2" box="[523,595,1013,1036]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">P. pyri</emphasis>
(Linné, 1758) (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="D96A4B17FFE1FFEB8798FBA3FE32FBC2" author="Colonnelli E." box="[210,397,1043,1068]" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 142" part="337" refString="Colonnelli E. 2003. A revised checklist of Italian Curculionoidea (Coleoptera). Zootaxa 337: 1 - 142." title="A revised checklist of Italian Curculionoidea (Coleoptera)" type="journal article" year="2003">Colonnelli, 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="D96A4B17FFE1FFEB86D1FBA3FDFBFBC2" author="Yunakov N. N." bookContentInfo="700 pp." box="[411,580,1043,1068]" editor="Lobl I" journalOrPublisher="Brill, Leiden" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" pagination="364 - 375" refString="Yunakov N. N. 2013. Polydrusini [pp. 364 - 375]. In: Lobl I. &amp; Smetana A. (eds). Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera, Vol. 8, Curculionoidea II. Brill, Leiden, 700 pp.." title="Polydrusini" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera, Vol. 8, Curculionoidea II" year="2013">Yunakov, 2013</bibRefCitation>
). While 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB85EFFBA3FF49FBA2" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Phyllobius pyri</emphasis>
lives mostly on arboreous 
<taxonomicName id="7AFB4D65FFE1FFEB8552FB85FDC2FBA2" authorityName="" authorityYear="1789" box="[536,637,1077,1100]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
and shows a more elongate body and a regularly coloured vestiture, 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB87DDFBC5FE93FB62" box="[151,300,1141,1164]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">P. vespertinus</emphasis>
is more xerothermophilous, lives on various herbaceous plants, its body is more stout, the elytra often with a striped vestiture. We here included further specimens from the southern side of the Alps, where the characters of 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB867BFB45FE76FAE2" box="[305,457,1269,1292]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">P. vespertinus</emphasis>
are well pronounced [and from there (Monte Rosa, Val d’Entremont, St. Bernhard) once described as separate taxon 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB8555FA86FD2FFAA3" box="[543,656,1334,1357]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">artemisiae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="D96A4B17FFE1FFEB85D4FA84FEABFA83" author="Desbrochers des Loges J." journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" pagination="118 - 119" part="1873" refString="Desbrochers des Loges J. 1873. [new taxa] Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France 1873: 118 - 119." title="[new taxa] Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France" type="journal article" year="1873">Desbrochers, 1873</bibRefCitation>
, junior synonym of 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB86AFFAE6FDC8FA83" box="[485,631,1366,1389]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">P. vespertinus</emphasis>
]. However, we provide further support that the taxa are not separable based on analyses of COI sequences (
<figureCitation id="25C02A63FFE1FFEB8577FA25FDC0FA43" box="[573,639,1429,1453]" captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,186,1908,1929]" captionTargetBox="[155,1408,263,1896]" captionTargetId="graphics@3.[544,992,642,2095]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Best Maximum Likelihood tree as selected by MEGA) based on COI sequences of 142 samples of Curculionoidea (Chrysomelidae obtained by using MEGA 6. Values (over 50 %) of bootstrap support from 100 nodes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1040870/files/figure.svg" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, Supp. 1), as already shown by 
<bibRefCitation id="D96A4B17FFE1FFEB8633FA05FDE8FA23" author="Schutte A. &amp; Stuben P. E. &amp; Sprick P." box="[377,599,1461,1485]" journalOrPublisher="A contribution to Integrative Taxonomy and Phylogenetic Systematics. Snudebiller" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 77" part="14" refString="Schutte A., Stuben P. E., Sprick P. 2013. The Molecular Weevil Identification Project (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea), Part I. A contribution to Integrative Taxonomy and Phylogenetic Systematics. Snudebiller 14 (211): 1 - 77." title="The Molecular Weevil Identification Project (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea), Part I" type="journal article" year="2013">
Schütte 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB869AFA06FE40FA22" box="[464,511,1461,1485]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">et al</emphasis>
. (2013)
</bibRefCitation>
. Similar to the 
<emphasis id="8F8FEAF4FFE1FFEB87DDFA66FED4FA03" box="[151,363,1494,1517]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">
<taxonomicName id="7AFB4D65FFE1FFEB87DDFA66FF58FA03" authorityName="Germar" authorityYear="1817" box="[151,231,1494,1517]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Hypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hypera</taxonomicName>
nigrirostris
</emphasis>
-group, COI might be not sensitive enough to show differences, due to recent (ecological) separation of the taxa (i. e. incomplete lineage sorting), and/or genetical interchange (hybridisation) might still occur.
</paragraph>
